The paper proposes a method for state estimation in power distribution networks using Bayesian estimation and linear least squares. This involves the use of Gaussian processes for load predictions and linear approximations for unbalanced three-phase power flow. These techniques are commonly used in machine learning and control systems, suggesting that cs.SY (Systems and Control) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses uncertainty and smoothing, which are topics in statistical learning and optimization, indicating that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.SE (Software Engineering) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper applies the method to different test feeders and validates it on a real test feeder, which suggests that cs.NE (Networking and Internet Architecture) may also be a relevant sub-category.
